window.NETPLUS_LESSONS_W2 = {"1":{"title":"TCP/IP Model Deep Dive","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"2\" data-day=\"1\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 2 · Day 1</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">TCP/IP Model Deep Dive</h2></header><h3>TCP/IP Layers</h3>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>TCP/IP Layer</th>\n<th>Comparable OSI Layers</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Application</td>\n<td>5–7</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Transport</td>\n<td>4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Internet</td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Network Access</td>\n<td>1–2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Encapsulation Process</h2>\n<p>Data moves downward:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Data</li>\n<li>Segment</li>\n<li>Packet</li>\n<li>Frame</li>\n<li>Bits</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2>Key Protocols</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Layer</th>\n<th>Protocols</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Application</td>\n<td>HTTP, DNS, FTP</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Transport</td>\n<td>TCP, UDP</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Internet</td>\n<td>IP, ICMP</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Network Access</td>\n<td>Ethernet</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>PDUs</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Layer</th>\n<th>PDU</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Application</td>\n<td>Data</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Transport</td>\n<td>Segment</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Network</td>\n<td>Packet</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Data Link</td>\n<td>Frame</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Physical</td>\n<td>Bits</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 2, Day 1</strong> (TCP/IP Model Deep Dive), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>TCP/IP layers vs OSI. Encapsulation/decapsulation. PDUs: bits, frames, packets, segments.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>TCP/IP Model Deep Dive</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Map each TCP/IP layer to the corresponding OSI layer(s).</li><li>Convert 11000000.10101000.00000001.00000001 to dotted decimal.</li><li>Which private IPv4 range uses 10.0.0.0/8?</li><li>For 192.168.1.0/26, what is the broadcast address?</li><li>Why is a default gateway required for hosts on different subnets?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Subnetting worksheet: given a network address and mask, identify network ID, broadcast, and valid host range (5 problems).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Create a subnet plan for a fictional small office with 3 departments from a /24 block.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Configure static IPv4 addresses on a multi-PC network with a router. Test inter-VLAN communication and document IP scheme in Packet Tracer.</p>\n</section></article>"},"2":{"title":"Binary & IP Addressing","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"2\" data-day=\"2\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 2 · Day 2</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Binary &amp; IP Addressing</h2></header><h3>Why Binary Matters</h3>\n<p>Computers communicate using binary.</p>\n<p>Binary uses:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>0</li>\n<li>1</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Binary Place Values</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Bit</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>128</td>\n<td>128</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>64</td>\n<td>64</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>32</td>\n<td>32</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>16</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>8</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Example Conversion</h2>\n<p>192 in binary:</p>\n<p>128 + 64 = 192</p>\n<p>Binary:</p>\n<p>11000000</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>IPv4 Structure</h2>\n<p>IPv4 contains:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>32 bits</li>\n<li>4 octets</li>\n<li>Dotted decimal notation</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<p>192.168.1.1</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Public vs Private IPs</h2>\n<h3>Private Ranges</h3>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Range</th>\n<th>Class</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>10.0.0.0–10.255.255.255</td>\n<td>A</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>172.16.0.0–172.31.255.255</td>\n<td>B</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>192.168.0.0–192.168.255.255</td>\n<td>C</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 2, Day 2</strong> (Binary & IP Addressing), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Binary number system, decimal-to-binary conversion. IPv4 structure: 4 octets, dotted decimal.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Binary &amp; IP Addressing</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Map each TCP/IP layer to the corresponding OSI layer(s).</li><li>Convert 11000000.10101000.00000001.00000001 to dotted decimal.</li><li>Which private IPv4 range uses 10.0.0.0/8?</li><li>For 192.168.1.0/26, what is the broadcast address?</li><li>Why is a default gateway required for hosts on different subnets?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Subnetting worksheet: given a network address and mask, identify network ID, broadcast, and valid host range (5 problems).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Create a subnet plan for a fictional small office with 3 departments from a /24 block.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Configure static IPv4 addresses on a multi-PC network with a router. Test inter-VLAN communication and document IP scheme in Packet Tracer.</p>\n</section></article>"},"3":{"title":"IP Classes & Subnets","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"2\" data-day=\"3\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 2 · Day 3</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">IP Classes &amp; Subnets</h2></header><h3>Classful Addressing</h3>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Class</th>\n<th>First Octet</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>A</td>\n<td>1–126</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>B</td>\n<td>128–191</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>C</td>\n<td>192–223</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>D</td>\n<td>224–239</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>E</td>\n<td>240–255</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Subnet Masks</h2>\n<p>Subnet masks separate:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Network portion</li>\n<li>Host portion</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<p>255.255.255.0</p>\n<p>Equivalent:</p>\n<p>/24</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>CIDR Notation</h2>\n<p>CIDR uses slash notation.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>/24</li>\n<li>/16</li>\n<li>/30</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 2, Day 3</strong> (IP Classes & Subnets), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Class A/B/C/D/E ranges, private vs public IP, APIPA. Subnet mask basics and slash notation (/24, /16).</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>IP Classes &amp; Subnets</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Map each TCP/IP layer to the corresponding OSI layer(s).</li><li>Convert 11000000.10101000.00000001.00000001 to dotted decimal.</li><li>Which private IPv4 range uses 10.0.0.0/8?</li><li>For 192.168.1.0/26, what is the broadcast address?</li><li>Why is a default gateway required for hosts on different subnets?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Subnetting worksheet: given a network address and mask, identify network ID, broadcast, and valid host range (5 problems).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Create a subnet plan for a fictional small office with 3 departments from a /24 block.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Configure static IPv4 addresses on a multi-PC network with a router. Test inter-VLAN communication and document IP scheme in Packet Tracer.</p>\n</section></article>"},"4":{"title":"Subnetting Fundamentals","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"2\" data-day=\"4\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 2 · Day 4</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Subnetting Fundamentals</h2></header><h3>Why Subnet?</h3>\n<p>Benefits:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Reduce broadcasts</li>\n<li>Improve security</li>\n<li>Better organization</li>\n<li>Efficient addressing</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Key Terms</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Definition</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Network Address</td>\n<td>First address</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Broadcast Address</td>\n<td>Last address</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Usable Hosts</td>\n<td>Assignable IPs</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Example</h2>\n<p>192.168.1.0/24</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Network: 192.168.1.0</li>\n<li>Broadcast: 192.168.1.255</li>\n<li>Hosts: 192.168.1.1–192.168.1.254</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 2, Day 4</strong> (Subnetting Fundamentals), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Why we subnet, calculating network/broadcast/host addresses. Step-by-step subnetting practice.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Subnetting Fundamentals</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Map each TCP/IP layer to the corresponding OSI layer(s).</li><li>Convert 11000000.10101000.00000001.00000001 to dotted decimal.</li><li>Which private IPv4 range uses 10.0.0.0/8?</li><li>For 192.168.1.0/26, what is the broadcast address?</li><li>Why is a default gateway required for hosts on different subnets?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Subnetting worksheet: given a network address and mask, identify network ID, broadcast, and valid host range (5 problems).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Create a subnet plan for a fictional small office with 3 departments from a /24 block.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Configure static IPv4 addresses on a multi-PC network with a router. Test inter-VLAN communication and document IP scheme in Packet Tracer.</p>\n</section></article>"},"5":{"title":"IP Configuration Lab","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"2\" data-day=\"5\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 2 · Day 5</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">IP Configuration Lab</h2></header><h3>Objectives</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Configure static IPs</li>\n<li>Configure default gateway</li>\n<li>Test communication</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Router Configuration</h2>\n<pre class=\"code-block\"><code class=\"language-bash\">enable\nconfigure terminal\ninterface g0/0\nip address 192.168.1.1 255.255.255.0\nno shutdown\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n<h2>Verification Commands</h2>\n<pre class=\"code-block\"><code class=\"language-bash\">show ip interface brief\nping\nipconfig\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 2, Day 5</strong> (IP Configuration Lab), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Configuring static IPs on routers and hosts. Reviewing ipconfig/ifconfig output and default gateways.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>IP Configuration Lab</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Map each TCP/IP layer to the corresponding OSI layer(s).</li><li>Convert 11000000.10101000.00000001.00000001 to dotted decimal.</li><li>Which private IPv4 range uses 10.0.0.0/8?</li><li>For 192.168.1.0/26, what is the broadcast address?</li><li>Why is a default gateway required for hosts on different subnets?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> Subnetting worksheet: given a network address and mask, identify network ID, broadcast, and valid host range (5 problems).</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Create a subnet plan for a fictional small office with 3 departments from a /24 block.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Configure static IPv4 addresses on a multi-PC network with a router. Test inter-VLAN communication and document IP scheme in Packet Tracer.</p>\n</section></article>"}};
